review:
TL;DR Soulslike, but in 2D

Wot I liked
- Same cute art style;
- Real deal DS-style online feature. You can help others, invade, protect or be invaded;
- Various enemy types;
- There are like 4 big maps to "explore";
- Some bosses actually have many cool moves;
- Fighting mage minibosses is quite fun. And there are many mage minibosses;
- You see most equipped gear;
- Monsters fight each other;
- Cool gestures. Unique 2 player emotes.

Wot I disliked
- Weapons have few moves and veer towards spamming;
- Combat feels unresponsive: your basic dodge seems to be designed for dodging huge monsters, so it's pretty useless in fighting normal-sized enemies, and huge enemies quite often are too big to be dodged, so dodge is pretty useless against them either;
- For some reason the skill tree occupies only 40% of the screen and on top of that it is zoomed in and cannot be zoomed out. Very unfriendly;
- The skill tree looks impressive when you see it for the first time, but you soon understand that it contains 2 things: stats and weapon/armour proficiency - nothing more;
- "Exploration" in this game deserve quotes - it's bare bones: open a door to hunt for a mage, hunt a mage to open a new door, repeat;
- You cannot track the mages you meet in the world which makes running after them confusing;
- Inventory management is a step back from your regular cumbersome unfriendly soulslike game;
- The game provides you almost no respec option - that's too cocky for an indie game;
- Game's too long. You have to hunt for the mages too much and the fights are not that different;
- Enemies can gank you at respawn;
- They make you watch through the end credits;
- Bugs, glitches;
- Coop might be broken: you are invaded or sent to people who sometimes are way out of your league.

To sum it all up, the biggest problem of this game that even though it looks nice on the surface… the surface is all that is there. All the mechanics are 1-inch deep, all you see in first 10 minutes of the game is basically all there's there.

What in the Nameless God's name happened here? How did we move from an amazing game to this godless abomination? 

- equipment system was reworked, for the worse, main weapon and side weapon are now tied into one thing, for some reason, you cannot double hand nor equip shield as necessary, you have to make do with the pre-made combos; 
- world building was reworked, for the worse, there is no more "world", now we have a central hub from which we teleport to the locations, and those locations are completely separated from one another, unlike, say, Dark Souls 3; 
- enemies are now dirt cheap, there is no point in learning anything, it's best to just power through everything with reckless abandon, if you're dying too much, just grind levels and power through; 
- speaking of world building again, there is no organic roadblock anymore (a gap that needs double jump, for instance), they have made literal doors with "kill this many enemies first" message, and I cannot fathom anything cheaper than this, it's ridiculous; 
- checkpoint system was reworked, for the worse, now you no longer have access to sanctuaries to ressuply, upgrade, do quests, no, now you have totems and everything is done in the central hub, and ressuplying was reworked too, now you need a specific item to ressuply heals, so it's perfectly possible, and easy even, to completely run out of healing, which I don't know if I should laugh or cry about, and even better, you don't have access to teleport between totems, and ressuplying is done manualy instead of automatic like previous game; 
- storytelling was reworked, instead of organic learning via reading in-game descriptions and piecing together the story through NPC's quest, enemy name, locations and whatnot, now we have a billion NPCs that vomit exposition as needed, lovely; 

Not all is lost, though... 

- leveling and item buying are still the same; 
- art style and overall presentation are still the same; 
- combat stream and momentum are still the same, despite the disgusting equipment system and cheap enemies; 

But I don't know if that alone can salvage this mess... The game overall is not the end of the world, it's still somewhat fun, albeit with very annoying changes, so if you can stomach the new disgusting equipment system and the insane cheapness of the enemies, it's worth a 60% sale. 
5.5/10 - don't buy it unless you are starved for a soulslike-platforming game and is absolutely bored of Salt and Sanctuary, otherwise just buy Salt and Sanctuary instead or wait for a big sale, at least 50%. 
As a final note, I hope Sweeney's money was worth it, because between EGS's terrible sales and game sub-mediocrity delivery, the sales won't save this tragedy of a game.

This is such a downgrade from Salt & Sanctuary. I understand trying to spice the formula by meshing mechanics from other games (Monster Hunter) but you can't just add things willy nilly.

- The mages you hunt is basically the same with a different coat of paint;
- The other bosses are all forgettable with simplistic moveset;
- Bosses are simplistic, but they don't have stamina and spam the sh** out of their AoE high damaging attacks;
- So, bosses spam attacks, your dodge consumes a lot of stamina and, the cherry on top, dodge covers a lot of ground, positioning you far from the boss so you can hit once, maybe twice before the boss start another attack;
- 90% of the attacks will send you flying or juggle you for potential combos, Tekken style;
- There's no map, which is not bad by itself, but when you need to chase mages around, it gets really tedious;
- Since you have to chase mages around, you still have to deal with trash mobs that can still kill you easily;
- Exploration is gutted, making the gear you use behind grinding mages materials;
- Grappling hook is very inconsistent. Don't know if it's my controller, but I fell to my death so much from this because the hook flashed for 1s and it didn't register the input. Don't have this problem in other games though.

4.5/10

I stopped after beating the Mech mage, whatever his name is, in Corvious Mire, so a don't know about the rest of the game, but i'm not willing to waste maybe another 10-20h to find out.

I read the mixed reviews from steam release before buying and waited for a good sale.
Payed dirt cheap and still got disappointed. What a shame, it blows my mind that this came from the creators of the amazing Salt & Sanctuary.
Another one on my list of "will never finish".
